snippet.title: Pune Porsche Accident: Excise Officials Seal 2 Bars That Sold Liquor To Minor
snippet.description:
Pune officials have sealed a city bar that served alcohol to a 17-year-old boy and his friends, after which the drunk teen drove and rammed a Porsche sports car into a bike carrying two people, both of whom were killed. CCTV footage from inside the premises confirmed liquor had been served to the boy and his friends. The legal drinking age in the state of Maharashtra is 25, which means it was illegal to serve liquor to the boy or his friends. The youngster was produced before the Juvenile Justice Board which granted him bail hours later. It also directed him to visit the Regional Transport Office and study traffic rules, and submit a presentation to the Board within 15 days. The teenager was directed to write an essay of 300 words on the topic of road accidents and their solutions. The board also directed the youth to be referred to an alcohol deaddiction centre for counselling. The quick bail in a case where two people had died, had drawn widespread criticism. The father of the teenager, as well as the owners of a couple of bars where the minor was served alcohol, have been arrested.

snippet.title: Pune Porsche Accident: Father of Pune teen driver arrested in Aurangabad
snippet.description:
The father of the 17-year-old boy has been arrested by Pune Police from Maharashtra's Aurangabad. 
The name old his father is Vishal Agrawal who is a a real estate developer. Following the accident, an FIR was lodged against Vishal Agrawal, and the accused immediately made escape plans.
In a bid to dodge capture, Agrawal executed a clever scheme. He initially drove his regular car towards Mumbai accompanied by his driver. Meanwhile, he dispatched another vehicle towards Goa and Kolhapur, throwing authorities off his trail. Throughout his escape, he kept his family in the dark, feeding them false information about his destination, insisting he was in route to Mumbai.
Agrawal took further steps to evade detection by switching off his main phone and adopting a new number to avoid tracking. Despite his efforts, authorities managed to trace his movements through the GPS of a friend's car, which he utilized to visit different places, including his farmhouse in Daund and properties in Pune.
Using advanced technology and GPS tracking, Pune Crime Branch teams worked diligently to locate Agrawal. They used CCTV footage and intercepted messages sent by Agrawal to his family. Finally, their efforts paid off when they found him hiding in a small lodge in Sambhajinagar.

snippet.title: Arnab Confronts Pune Police Commissioner Amitesh Kumar In Explosive LIVE Segment |Pune Porsche Crash
snippet.description:
Republic Media Network's Editor-in-Chief Arnab Goswami confronted Pune Police Commissioner Amitesh Kumar on LIVE TV over the Pune Porsche crash. Here's an excerpt of the heated conversatio:

Amitesh Kumar: Our stand is vindicated, 100% it is vindicated.
Arnab: Sir your stand is not vindicated, sir it is a powerful family, sir it is a super rich family of Pune, which is trying to push its way through 
Amitesh Kumar: Our course gets affected by what the law says
Arnab: Sir don't teach me the law, I also understand the law well enough, you can have 304, 304A 
Amitesh Kumar: If you know the law please don't misguide the people, our outcome is very clear 
Arnab: Sir, I am not misguiding the people, I'm telling you sir, please don't wag your finger at me 
Amitesh Kumar: You will also have to keep your finger down
Arnab: I will keep my fingers down, but do not try to intimidate me, I know enough about the system, I am asking you now
Amitesh Kumar: If you can point fingers so can I
Arnab: I am not pointing fingers, I am asking questions that may not be convenient to you, but I will ask you repeatedly, you tell me why were two blood samples taken after a gap of 3-4 hours?
Amitesh Kumar: To ensure that there is no tampering 
Arnab: While you admit the gap of 4 hours can influence the result 
Amitesh Kumar: Primarily to check the DNA sample, that in case the blood was taken at the first instance was the same of the accused, that was the reason 
Arnab: As a precaution?
Amitesh Kumar: Yes
Arnab: Was the result of the two samples the same?
Amitesh Kumar: The results haven't come, I told you, the results are awaited, it is with the forensic department

snippet.title: Pune Accident | Pune Teen Who Killed 2 People With Porsche Got Bail In 15 Hours
snippet.description:
Pune Accident: The 17-year-old boy at the wheel of the speeding Porsche that hit a bike in Pune Saturday night, killing a man and a woman, was out on bail 15 hours after he was arrested. His lawyer Prashant Patil said a court granted bail to the minor on conditions -- he has to work with traffic police in Yerwada for 15 days, write an essay on accidents, undergo treatment for his drinking habit, and take counselling sessions. The accused is the son of a prominent Pune realtor.

Twenty-four-year-olds Aneesh Awadhiya and Ashwini Koshta, both engineers from Madhya Pradesh working in Pune, were returning on a bike after attending a get-together with friends. The Porsche, which eyewitnesses have said was driving at over 200 km per hour and had no number plates, hit the bike. Ashwini was thrown about 20 feet in the air and landed hard, said an eyewitness. Aneesh was thrown at a parked car and suffered serious injuries. Both died on the spot.

snippet.title: Pune Porsche accident: “Driver pressurized and threatened”, reveals Pune CP Amitesh Kumar
snippet.description:
Pune Commissioner of Police, Amitsh Kumar, revealed on May 25 that the driver was given all kinds of temptations, then pressurized and even threatened to accept that he was driving the car. In a shocking incident on May 19, builder Vishal Agarwal‘s 17-year-old son allegedly drove his father’s Porsche while intoxicated and collided with a motorcycle, killing both riders.
CP Amitesh Kumar said, “When the driver was first brought to the Police Station from the spot, the first statement which he gave in writing was that he was driving the car. But the Police Station at that point of time disbelieved the statement of the driver and after a preliminary inquiry, they registered an offense against the juvenile accused because it was evident prima facie that the juvenile accused was driving the vehicle. The driver was given all kinds of temptations like money etc. and then was even threatened.”
